I'm having a bit of the same discussion in the /adhg/ thread so I'll reiterate what I wrote there across a few posts.

>I'm aware it's drifting away from /adhg/ territory. I started with the prompt of "man dominated by less physically powerful anthro who has social or hierarchical power over him." I got to that place really quickly and I could have gone with Charlotte staying a bitch, the staff being awful, and the facility not giving a shit in general, but that felt like a less interesting turn for the story even if it was truer to the /adhg/ roots. I grew to like the characters and I wanted to give them more depth. I also wanted to build a more complicated world than "everyone sucks here because the author says so".

>It was always in the plan for Charlotte to soften as she was around Jake. The idea was she was missing out on a big part of her life as a result of not having a partner. >My desire to write CotW really solidified when I was trying to come up with a good motivation for her(Charlotte) and outlined her origin story. Jake may be the protagonist, but I had Charlotte's character figured out much earlier than his.

Its a "show don't tell" lesson, because so far I've only told you or implied what Jake was like. When it really should have been shown, and shown first.

Anonymous Tue 07 Jul 2020 20:12:03 No.31361896 Report

>>31361646
Don't beat yourself too much over it, if you were to re-write your story every time you realized you could have done something better (which is absolutely inevitable given how writing works and how the story develops) you'd end up re-writing your story every time. Maybe the time will come when you'll want to tweak the beginning, but I'd say that winging it and focusing on what's ahead instead of rewriting the past is a better option. I don't know how much the metaphor holds, but I've seen a lot of really old webcomics who started out with objectively bad art that spent too much time ouroboros'ing themselves into nothingness because they wanted to redo everything now that they were better/things could have been done better. That usually is a shitton of work more than it's worth in the visual story medium for almost no reward, (which is why I think my metaphor isn't watertight) but it should still be a decent example: those people read your stuff even if it wasn't up to your standards. Rewriting it is mostly a waste of time unless you're going to completely change the very basics of the plot around, if the first readers thought it wasn't that big a deal then it most likely isn't worth going back obsessing to. Another methaphor (I'm sorry I'm full of those today) would be that it's like you're carving a tool you're going to be using to move an obstacle away from your course, and you did a rough but serviceable cut on what's gonna be the handle and instead of moving towards of finishing it so you can move forward you're going back to polishing the handle, while you know that the only way of progressing is finishing the tool even if it's not perfect.

So my advice would be to keep expanding and working on fleshing out than going back and fixing things.

By the way, nice story.

There are a couple "generations" of furs, the earliest ones like Dr. Hopper were sterile, some could only produce daughters that were clones of the mother, others produced human males and daughters (and took in more genetic variety from their father), later ones had full control over the sex of the child through hormonal supplements. >Also do human female have have Male furs? If not then why?

They did its just the total numbers were too different. Lots of men wanted 'furs, few women did. Lots of 'furs wanted large families, few women in developed nations wanted large families. There were gay and lesbian 'furs too, but the setting was dictated by the preference and ease with which younger straight men (or divorcees, or widowers) could just order a brand new wife to fit their liking.

Human females could only produce human offspring so that unbalanced things further. The male furs that existed basically had to have completely human sperm in order for human females to get pregnant. But the female furs, being artificial, had a lot of technological "cheats" (like the cloning) to control which offspring they had. Human women were limited by nature in ways 'furs were not.

Basically take every idea of what people in these threads would design "their ideal waifur" with and then think about how those things would scale. The guy that wants a waifur that just produces a bunch of fur daughters doesn't realize that there are a few million other guys doing the same thing, and each of them has 3-4 daughters and no sons to compensate the next generation with. Evolution balanced things with randomness, but people practicing armchair eugenics quickly fucked everything up.

I know I'm a bit late to the party, but as someone who is dying to see what happens next in your story, I even think the wisest course of action would be to flesh out the intro. Like you said, it would make Jake's current characterization all the more important, and let new readers get into this great story way easier than the current intro allows for the majority of new readers.

I personally love the 'Incels and Stacys bring unforseen consequences' angle of the story; while obviously a meme, it's much more rich and relevant than I think a lot of people are giving it credit for. If we strip away the furry aspect and look at the issue through real world perspective, it's quite frightening to realize the extent of things like this already being developed.

They're like accidental Terminators, nearly causing the extinction of man purely out of love, created from man's hubris.
